<TITLE>Editorial: Bad drivers a worse problem than bad roads</TITLE>


<TEXT>
Theres been far too much carnage on the roads around Chico <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DATE" value="PAST_REF">recently</TIMEX3>, the latest being the <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">crash</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="TIME" value="2017-01-29TEV">last Sunday evening</TIMEX3> on Highway 32 that <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">killed</EVENT> beloved Pleasant Valley High School coach and teacher Brett Silva. 
 
It was the second fatal <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">accident</EVENT> on 32 between Chico and Orland since <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="2017-11">November</TIMEX3>. November also <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">saw</EVENT> a double fatal on Highway 99 north of town. 
 
All of the crashes <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">occurred</EVENT> on two-lane highways. As weve <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">pointed</EVENT> out before, Chico is largest city in California that cant be <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">accessed</EVENT> by a four-lane road. To <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">get</EVENT> here youre going to have to <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">drive</EVENT> 20 miles or more with cars <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">zipping</EVENT> by in the other direction just a few feet away. 
 
Theres little margin for error, and with two oncoming vehicles combined speed in excess of 100 mph, if one <EVENT eid="e11" class="OCCURRENCE">slips</EVENT> into the others lane, the results are likely to be disastrous. 
 
Were not <EVENT eid="e12" class="I_STATE">expecting</EVENT> Caltrans to <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">build</EVENT> a four-lane connector anytime soon, so its hard to <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">blame</EVENT> the roads. That small margin of error we mention <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">requires</EVENT> an error, and its not possible to engineer away recklessness, drunkenness or inattentiveness. 
 
On Highway 32, Caltrans in <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DATE" value="PAST_REF">recent years</TIMEX3> has <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">rebuilt</EVENT> the bridge over Stony Creek and <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">moved</EVENT> the dangerous intersection of River Road a 100 yards or so east to a much safer <EVENT eid="e18" class="OCCURRENCE">location</EVENT>. Left-turn <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">pockets</EVENT> have been <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">added</EVENT> and the road has been <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">repaved</EVENT> and <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">striped</EVENT> with markings that you can actually <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">see</EVENT> at night. If you <EVENT eid="e24" class="I_ACTION">want</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">go</EVENT> back a few <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DURATION" value="PXY">more years</TIMEX3>, the frighteningly narrow Gianella Bridge was <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">replaced</EVENT>. 
 
Were not sure what more can be <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">done</EVENT> with asphalt and concrete, short of the <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">expansion</EVENT> thats not <EVENT eid="e29" class="I_STATE">realistic</EVENT> to expect  look at how long the planned four-lane artery from Chico to Sacramento has <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">languished</EVENT>. Perhaps the oncoming lanes could be <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">separated</EVENT>, but even that doesnt guarantee safety. 
 
Its the same with Highway 99 north of town. Caltrans made improvements including rumble strips to tell drivers when they were <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">leaving</EVENT> their lane, but again what more is there, unless the lanes could be physically <EVENT eid="e33" class="I_STATE">separated</EVENT>? 
 
Its hard to <EVENT eid="e34" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> that, as a couple of these crashes have <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">reached</EVENT> into the newsroom at this newspaper, and they <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">hurt</EVENT>. But you cant idiot-proof a road. 
 
One thing that could be <EVENT eid="e37" class="OCCURRENCE">done</EVENT> is the Highway Patrol could <EVENT eid="e38" class="I_STATE">dedicate</EVENT> a little more manpower to the states two-lane highways, which have so much more potential to be deadly. Have a presence. Enforce the laws. 
 
And then, make the traffic schools bad drivers use to <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">clear</EVENT> their records less of a joke, figuratively and literally. How in heck do comedy traffic schools get <EVENT eid="e40" class="OCCURRENCE">approved</EVENT> by the state? Add a little rigor to that process and maybe some responsibility can be <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">hammered</EVENT> into a few thick skulls. 
 
 
Ultimately highway safety <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">comes</EVENT> down to driver safety. Weve <EVENT eid="e43" class="STATE">had</EVENT> callers and letter writers say theyre afraid of the highways around Chico, and thats actually a good thing. Driving afraid is <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">driving</EVENT> cautious, and the more cautious drivers on the road the better. 
 
But the state has to <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">go</EVENT> after the fools who arent afraid, if the rest of us are to be safe.
</TEXT>


